Making predictions

Ben Whalley, Paul Sharpe, Sonja Heintz, Chris Berry

Adding best fit lines with geom_smooth()

  • Video summary
  • Code examples
  • Video Transcript

To make predictions from the data we need to draw a line of best fit.

In simple regression, we create a linear (straight line) model of the relationship between one outcome variable and one predictor variable

  • The outcome variable is what we want to predict or explain (e.g., anxiety scores)

  • The predictor variable is what we use to predict the outcome variable (e.g., average hours of screen time per week)

  • Both the outcome and predictor variable are continuous variables

A best fit line can represent what we think the actual relationship between the two variables is, everything else being equal. There are lots of ways to draw a best fit line, and we can use many different types of data, but in this session we will be sticking with straight lines and continous variables.

The simplest way to ‘see’ a simple linear regression is to use the geom_smooth(). This can add a line of best fit to our existing scatter plot.

mentalh %>%
  ggplot(aes(screen_time, anxiety_score)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm)

Explanation of the code: We used geom_point to create a scatterplot. Then we used a plus symbol (+) and added geom_smooth(method=lm) to add the fitted line. By default, geom_smooth would try to fit a curvy line through your datapoints, but adding method=lm makes it a straight line.

Explanation of the resulting plot The plot above is just like the scatter plots we drew before, but adds the blue fitted line. The blue line shows the ‘line of best fit’. Ignore the shaded area for now (or add geom_smooth(se=F) to hide it).

library(psydata)
library(tidyverse)

# make a scatterplot with a fitted line overlaid
mentalh %>%
  ggplot(aes(screen_time, anxiety_score)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm)

We can make a scatterplot as previously:

mentalh %>%
  ggplot(aes(screen_time, anxiety_score)) +
  geom_point()

It’s common that we place variables that we consider outcomes on the y axis of the plot and predictors on the x-axis, as here.

If we want to add a line to the plot we can use the geom_smooth function:

mentalh %>%
  ggplot(aes(screen_time, anxiety_score)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

By default geom_smooth draws this wiggly line on the data. It uses uses a technique called Loess smoothing to draw the line.

It’s often quite useful to have the wiggly line because it shows the general trend in the relationship.

However in this case we want to see the linear line of best fit, because that will correspond with the simple linear regression we want to run.

To do that we just add method=lm to the geom_smooth part

So now we see this blue line which is the line of best fit — it’s the linear relationship between the predictor and the outcome.

You can ignore the shaded are for now — it shows the standard error of the line, which is a way of saying how confident we are about the predictions it makes. But, if it bugs you, you can add se=F to the call and it will hide it.
